    publishDate: 'March 2026',
    ctaText: 'Get Your Free Contract Review',
    ctaSubtext: 'No obligation. Our attorneys review your contract and identify your options.',
    content: [
      { type: 'h2', content: `The Silence After the Storm: What Sunnova's Bankruptcy Really Means for You` },
      { type: 'p', content: `You remember the day they knocked on your door. They spoke of "energy independence," "guaranteed savings," and a "brighter future" for your family. You weren't looking for a complicated financial entanglement; you just wanted to do the right thing for the planet and your wallet. But now, the headlines are screaming about Sunnova's Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing, and that "brighter future" feels like a looming shadow over your home. If you feel a knot in your stomach, please know this: you are not alone. Thousands of hardworking homeowners across the country are waking up to the same news, feeling the same sense of betrayal. You didn't do anything wrong. You were targeted by a sophisticated sales machine that prioritized growth over people, and now you're left holding the bag.` },
      { type: 'p', content: `The news of Sunnova filing for bankruptcy on June 8, 2025, isn't just a corporate statistic; it's a personal crisis for families who trusted them. With over $10 billion in debt and a business model that relied heavily on third-party dealers, the collapse was a slow-motion train wreck that many saw coming--except for the homeowners who were kept in the dark. But here is the most important thing you need to hear today: there is hope, and there is a way out. Bankruptcy doesn't mean you are trapped forever. In fact, it might be the very thing that opens the door to your freedom.` },
      { type: 'h2', content: `Is My Sunnova Solar Contract Still Valid?` },
      { type: 'p', content: `The short answer is: yes, for now. In a Chapter 11 bankruptcy, the company is attempting to restructure or sell its assets. This means your solar contract cancellation isn't automatic. Your lease or Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) is considered a "financial asset" of the bankruptcy estate. However, the "validity" of a contract is a two-way street. If Sunnova or the installers they partnered with used solar fraud or deceptive tactics to get you to sign, the bankruptcy doesn't suddenly make those lies legal. You still have legal rights, and the chaos of a bankruptcy often exposes the very cracks in their paperwork that can lead to your relief.` },
      { type: 'quote', content: `"No one wants a delay, but this may actually work in your favor. Bankruptcy puts everything on the table, and while it slows things down, it may create new legal options we can pursue on your behalf." -- Neal Prevost, Consumer Protection Attorney` },
      { type: 'h3', content: `Can I cancel a solar contract if I was lied to about savings?` },
      { type: 'p', content: `Absolutely. If you were promised that your utility bill would disappear, or if you were told the system would produce more energy than it actually does, you may have a claim for misrepresentation. Under consumer protection law, a contract built on a foundation of lies is often voidable. While the bankruptcy puts a temporary "stay" on direct lawsuits against Sunnova, it does not stop you from challenging the underlying debt or pursuing the lenders and installers who were complicit in the deception. Many homeowners are finding that their right of rescission or other state-specific protections are more powerful than they realized.` },
      { type: 'h3', content: `What happens to my solar warranty if Sunnova goes out of business?` },
      { type: 'p', content: `This is the question that keeps most homeowners up at night. If Sunnova's assets are sold to another company (like Solaris or SunStrong Management), those warranties should transfer. However, "should" is a cold comfort when your inverter stops working and no one answers the phone. This uncertainty is exactly why so many people are looking for a way to cancel Sunnova solar contracts now. You shouldn't have to spend the next 20 years wondering if your multi-thousand-dollar system will become a "roof anchor" because the company responsible for it vanished.` },
      { type: 'h2', content: `The Psychological Trap: Why It's Hard to Walk Away` },
      { type: 'p', content: `The solar industry often uses a psychological principle called loss aversion. They make you feel like if you don't sign right now, you're losing out on thousands in tax credits or "locked-in" rates. Now that the company is in trouble, you might feel a different kind of trap: the "sunk cost fallacy." You've already paid so much, or you've had the panels for years, so you feel like you have to stick it out. Don't fall for it. Your home is your sanctuary, not a billboard for a bankrupt corporation's failed business model. You deserve peace of mind, and that starts with realizing that you have the power to change your situation.` },
      { type: 'h3', content: `Can I stop making payments to Sunnova during bankruptcy?` },
      { type: 'p', content: `This is a dangerous path to take without legal guidance. While it's tempting to stop paying a company that has failed you, doing so unilaterally can damage your credit or lead to a lien on your home. However, there are legal ways to "escrow" payments or challenge the debt through the bankruptcy court. The goal isn't just to stop paying; it's to legally dissolve the obligation so you can move on with your life. If you're in a state like California or Texas, there are specific statutes that might offer you a faster exit ramp.` },
      { type: 'h2', content: `What You Can Do Right Now` },
      { type: 'p', content: `The worst thing you can do is nothing. Bankruptcy moves fast, and your window to assert your rights as a creditor or a victim of fraud can close. Here is your immediate action plan:` },
      { type: 'h3', content: `Gather Your Paperwork: Find your original contract, any emails from the sales rep, and your utility bills from before and after the installation.Document System Failures: If your panels aren't producing what was promised, take screenshots of your monitoring app (if it's still working) and save your recent bills.Check Your State Laws: Every state has different rules for solar contract cancellation. Visit our guide on how to get out of a solar contract to see what applies to you.Seek Authority: Don't rely on the "customer service" line of a bankrupt company. Talk to experts who specialize in consumer protection law and solar disputes.

How do I know if my solar contract was fraudulent?` },
      { type: 'p', content: `Look for the "Red Flags": Did they sign the contract for you? Did they promise a "government stimulus check" that was actually just a tax credit you didn't qualify for? Did they tell you the panels would increase your home value, but now you can't sell your house because of the lien? If any of this sounds familiar, you weren't just "sold" a system--you were defrauded. And the law is on your side.` },
      { type: 'h2', content: `A Brighter Future is Still Possible` },
      { type: 'p', content: `Solar technology is a miracle of the modern age. It can provide clean, cheap energy for decades. But that technology shouldn't come at the cost of your financial security or your mental health. Sunnova's bankruptcy is a wake-up call for the entire industry, but for you, it's an opportunity to reclaim your home. You are not a "victim" anymore; you are an informed homeowner taking action. We have helped thousands of people just like you break free from predatory contracts and find the peace they deserve. Don't let another day go by feeling trapped. Visit breakyoursolarcontract.com today and let us help you turn the lights back on in your financial life.` }
    ],
